<subSubSection lastPageId="51" lastPageNumber="52" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" type="key">
<keyStep pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
<paragraph blockId="50.[151,1436,1574,2013]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
<keyLead pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
1 Head with a transverse groove at level of posterior margin of eyes; males with a tooth at apical one-third of posterior margin of mesofemur and of metafemur (
<figureCitation box="[640,796,1606,1629]" captionStart="FIGURES 149–155" captionStartId="53.[151,270,1530,1554]" captionTargetBox="[241,1342,542,1497]" captionTargetId="figure-269@53.[236,1352,534,1504]" captionTargetPageId="53" captionText="FIGURES 149–155. Platyhydnobius validus. 149. Right antenna, dorsal view. 150. Mandibles, dorsal view. 151. Male right mesofemur. 152. Male right metafemur. 153. Aedeagus, dorsal view. 154. Female sternite 8, ventral view. 155. Female coxites and styli, ventral view. Scale bar = 0.3 mm (Fig. 155), 0.4 mm (Fig. 154), 0.5 mm (Figs. 149, 150, 153), 1.0 mm (Figs. 151, 152)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310998" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310998/files/figure.png" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Figs. 151, 152</figureCitation>
); larger species, length of pronotum + elytra about 
<quantity box="[1342,1403,1606,1629]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" unit="mm" value="4.0">4 mm</quantity>
... ....................................................................................................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peck &amp; Cook" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Brown" baseAuthorityYear="1932" box="[1331,1435,1638,1662]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Platyhydnobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="validus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1331,1435,1638,1662]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">P. validus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="50.[151,1436,1574,2013]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
<keyLead pageId="50" pageNumber="51">- Head without a transverse groove; all male femora without teeth; smaller species, length of pronotum + elytra less than 3.5 mm .................................................................................................................................................................. 2</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
<paragraph blockId="50.[151,1436,1574,2013]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
<keyLead pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
2 Paramere apices broad, very thin, one-third of paramere length extends beyond apex of median lobe (
<figureCitation box="[1327,1423,1734,1757]" captionStart="FIGURES 143–147" captionStartId="51.[151,271,1764,1788]" captionTargetBox="[258,1326,970,1740]" captionTargetId="figure-326@51.[254,1332,964,1740]" captionTargetPageId="51" captionText="FIGURES 143–147. Platyhydnobius arizonensis. 143. Right antenna, dorsal view. 144. Mandibles, dorsal view. 145. Aedeagus, dorsal view. 146. Female sternite 8, ventral view. 147. Female coxites and styli, ventral view. Scale bar = 0.3 mm (Figs. 145, 147), 0.4 mm (Fig. 146), 0.5 mm (Figs. 143, 144)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310991" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310991/files/figure.png" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Fig. 145</figureCitation>
); northern transcontinental and south to 
<collectingRegion box="[610,696,1766,1789]" country="United States of America" name="Arizona" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Arizona</collectingRegion>
...................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Horn" authorityYear="1885" box="[1285,1436,1766,1790]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Hydnobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arizonensis">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1285,1436,1766,1790]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">P. arizonensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="50.[151,1436,1574,2013]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
<keyLead pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
- Parameres shorter, one-third of length not extending beyond apex of median lobe (e.g. 
<figureCitation box="[1153,1256,1798,1821]" captionStart="FIGURES 156–159" captionStartId="54.[151,272,1773,1797]" captionTargetBox="[254,1337,1087,1747]" captionTargetId="figure-380@54.[249,1337,1082,1748]" captionTargetPageId="54" captionText="FIGURES 156–159. Platyhydnobius andersoni. 156. Right antenna, dorsal view. 157. Aedeagus, dorsal view. 158. Female sternite 8, ventral view. 159. Female coxites and styli, ventral view. Scale bar = 0.3 mm (Fig. 159), 0.4 mm (Fig. 158), 0.5 mm (Figs. 156, 157)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5311000" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5311000/files/figure.png" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Figs. 157</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1269,1313,1798,1821]" captionStart="FIGURES 161–162" captionStartId="56.[151,270,1243,1267]" captionTargetBox="[335,1258,551,1213]" captionTargetId="figure-370@56.[329,1258,545,1216]" captionTargetPageId="56" captionText="FIGURES 161–162. Platyhydnobius bicolor. 161. Right antenna, dorsal view. 162. Aedeagus, dorsal view. Scale bar = 0.4 mm (Fig. 162), 0.5 mm (Fig. 161)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5311006" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5311006/files/figure.png" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">162</figureCitation>
); known to occur in 
<collectingCountry box="[292,373,1830,1853]" name="Mexico" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Mexico</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[425,528,1830,1853]" name="Honduras" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Honduras</collectingCountry>
[females of these species can be reliably identified only by association with males]. ...................................................................................................................................................................................... 3
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
<paragraph blockId="50.[151,1436,1574,2013]" box="[151,1436,1894,1918]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,1894,1918]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
3 Median lobe of aedeagus apically truncate (
<figureCitation box="[666,757,1894,1917]" captionStart="FIGURES 163–164" captionStartId="57.[151,269,1039,1063]" captionTargetBox="[344,1250,278,1008]" captionTargetId="figure-340@57.[338,1250,274,1012]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="FIGURES 163–164. Platyhydnobius calvario. 163. Right antenna, dorsal view. 164. Aedeagus, dorsal view. Scale bar = 0.5 mm (Figs. 163, 164)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5311008" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5311008/files/figure.png" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Fig. 164</figureCitation>
) ................................................................................. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peck &amp; Cook" authorityYear="2009" box="[1321,1436,1894,1918]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Platyhydnobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="calvario">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1321,1436,1894,1918]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">P. calvario</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="50.[151,1436,1574,2013]" box="[151,1435,1926,1949]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
<keyLead box="[151,1435,1926,1949]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">- Median lobe of aedeagus apically narrow or lobed, not truncate ............................................................................... 4</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<paragraph blockId="50.[151,1436,1574,2013]" box="[151,1436,1958,1982]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,1958,1982]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
<keyStep box="[151,1436,1958,1982]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
4 Median lobe of aedeagus abruptly narrowed to small apical lobe (
<figureCitation box="[900,987,1958,1981]" captionStart="FIGURES 165–166" captionStartId="58.[151,270,849,873]" captionTargetBox="[346,1245,204,816]" captionTargetId="figure-415@58.[341,1245,197,822]" captionTargetPageId="58" captionText="FIGURES 165–166. Platyhydnobius howdenorum. 165. Right antenna, dorsal view. 166. Aedeagus, dorsal view. Scale bar = 0.4 mm (Fig. 166), 0.5 mm (Fig. 165)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5311010" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5311010/files/figure.png" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Fig. 166</figureCitation>
)...................................... 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peck &amp; Cook" authorityYear="2009" box="[1265,1436,1958,1982]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Platyhydnobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="howdenorum">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1265,1436,1958,1982]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">P. howdenorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyStep>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="50.[151,1436,1574,2013]" lastBlockId="51.[151,1436,152,464]" lastPageId="51" lastPageNumber="52" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
<keyLead box="[151,1435,1990,2013]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">- Median lobe of aedeagus gradually narrowed apically ............................................................................................... 5</keyLead>
<keyLead pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
<keyStep pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
5 Median lobe of aedeagus evenly rounded apically (
<figureCitation box="[752,846,152,175]" captionStart="FIGURES 156–159" captionStartId="54.[151,272,1773,1797]" captionTargetBox="[254,1337,1087,1747]" captionTargetId="figure-380@54.[249,1337,1082,1748]" captionTargetPageId="54" captionText="FIGURES 156–159. Platyhydnobius andersoni. 156. Right antenna, dorsal view. 157. Aedeagus, dorsal view. 158. Female sternite 8, ventral view. 159. Female coxites and styli, ventral view. Scale bar = 0.3 mm (Fig. 159), 0.4 mm (Fig. 158), 0.5 mm (Figs. 156, 157)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5311000" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5311000/files/figure.png" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Fig. 157</figureCitation>
); each paramere with a single large preapical seta dorsally (
<figureCitation box="[264,356,184,207]" captionStart="FIGURES 156–159" captionStartId="54.[151,272,1773,1797]" captionTargetBox="[254,1337,1087,1747]" captionTargetId="figure-380@54.[249,1337,1082,1748]" captionTargetPageId="54" captionText="FIGURES 156–159. Platyhydnobius andersoni. 156. Right antenna, dorsal view. 157. Aedeagus, dorsal view. 158. Female sternite 8, ventral view. 159. Female coxites and styli, ventral view. Scale bar = 0.3 mm (Fig. 159), 0.4 mm (Fig. 158), 0.5 mm (Figs. 156, 157)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5311000" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5311000/files/figure.png" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Fig. 157</figureCitation>
); body broadly ovate, ratio elytral length:width = 1:0.9; elytral bases with a narrow transverse yellow band ........................................................................................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peck &amp; Cook" authorityYear="2009" box="[1300,1435,216,240]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Platyhydnobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="andersoni">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1300,1435,216,240]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">P. andersoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyStep>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="51.[151,1436,152,464]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
<keyLead pageId="51" pageNumber="52">- Median lobe of aedeagus not evenly rounded apically; each paramere with 2 large preapical setae dorsally; body narrower, ratio elytral length:width = 1:0.8 or less; elytral coloration not as above ........................................................ 6</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<keyStep pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
<paragraph blockId="51.[151,1436,152,464]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
<keyLead pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
6 Elytra yellowish with a broad black lateral border than does not reach the base, and a narrow black sutural border .. 
<emphasis box="[206,1436,344,368]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
........................................................................................................................................................................ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peck &amp; Cook" authorityYear="2009" box="[1333,1436,344,368]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Platyhydnobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicolor">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1333,1436,344,368]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">P. bicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="51.[151,1436,152,464]" box="[151,1435,376,399]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
<keyLead box="[151,1435,376,399]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">- Elytra coloration not as above .................................................................................................................................... 7</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
<paragraph blockId="51.[151,1436,152,464]" box="[151,1436,408,432]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,408,432]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
7 Apex of median lobe narrow (
<figureCitation box="[521,614,408,431]" captionStart="FIGURES 172–175" captionStartId="60.[151,271,1049,1073]" captionTargetBox="[256,1342,354,1013]" captionTargetId="figure-350@60.[244,1342,351,1022]" captionTargetPageId="60" captionText="FIGURES 172–175. Platyhydnobius newtonorum. 172. Right antenna, dorsal view. 173. Aedeagus, dorsal view. 174. Female sternite 8, ventral view. 175. Female coxites and styli, ventral view. Scale bar = 0.3 mm (Fig. 175), 0.4 mm (Figs. 173, 174), 0.5 mm (Fig. 172)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5311016" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5311016/files/figure.png" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Fig. 173</figureCitation>
). 
<collectingCountry box="[633,715,408,431]" name="Mexico" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Mexico</collectingCountry>
................................................................................. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peck &amp; Cook" authorityYear="2009" box="[1270,1436,408,432]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Platyhydnobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="newtonorum">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1270,1436,408,432]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">P. newtonorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="51.[151,1436,152,464]" box="[151,1436,440,464]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,440,464]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
- Apex of median lobe broadly rounded (
<figureCitation box="[621,714,440,463]" captionStart="FIGURES 167–171" captionStartId="59.[151,274,1059,1083]" captionTargetBox="[247,1340,282,1024]" captionTargetId="figure-358@59.[243,1343,274,1032]" captionTargetPageId="59" captionText="FIGURES 167–171. Platyhydnobius latigra. 167. Right antenna, dorsal view. 168. Mandibles, dorsal view. 169. Aedeagus, dorsal view. 170. Female sternite 8, ventral view. 171. Female coxites and styli, ventral view. Scale bar = 0.3 mm (Figs. 168, 171), 0.4 mm (Figs. 169, 170), 0.5 mm (Fig. 167)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5311012" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5311012/files/figure.png" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Fig. 169</figureCitation>
). 
<collectingCountry box="[733,835,440,463]" name="Honduras" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Honduras</collectingCountry>
......................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peck &amp; Cook" authorityYear="2009" box="[1337,1436,440,464]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Platyhydnobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latigra">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1337,1436,440,464]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">P. latigra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
